  "prompt": "How is aqueous copper nitrate determined?",
  "response": "Aqueous copper nitrate can be determined through several analytical methods:\n\n1. Gravimetric Analysis\n- Precipitate copper as copper(II) hydroxide\n- Convert to copper oxide\n- Weigh the resulting copper oxide\n- Calculate copper nitrate concentration\n\n2. Spectrophotometric Methods\n- Use UV-visible spectroscopy\n- Measure absorbance at specific wavelengths\n- Calibration curve technique\n- Determine concentration based on color intensity\n\n3. Volumetric Titration\n- Complexometric titration with EDTA\n- Indicator like Eriochrome Black T\n- Determine copper ion concentration\n\n4. Atomic Absorption Spectroscopy (AAS)\n- Measure copper ion absorption\n- High precision and sensitivity\n- Direct determination of copper concentration\n\n5. Inductively Coupled Plasma (ICP) Methods\n- ICP-Optical Emission Spectroscopy\n- ICP-Mass Spectroscopy\n- Highly accurate and sensitive\n- Detect trace amounts of copper\n\n6. Electrochemical Methods\n- Voltammetry\n- Potentiometry\n- Measure electrical properties related to copper concentration\n\nEach method has specific advantages and is chosen based on required precision, sample characteristics, and available equipment.",
